      </p>
      
      
      
      <h4>8.1.5. Advisory Boards</h4>
      
      <p>It is commonly accepted practice to appoint advisory boards to large projects and to those of extended duration. Board members
         should include subject specialists and technical experts. Their role is to shape the overall goals and objectives of the collection,
         to confirm that the project remains on course over time, and to address emerging issues.
      </p>
      
      <p><b>Recommended Advisory Board Models</b></p>
      
      <p>BIOME Special Advisory Group on Evaluation. Available at <a href="http://biome.ac.uk/sage/">http://biome.ac.uk/sage/</a>.
      </p>
      
      <p>Edinburgh Engineering Virtual Library (EEVL). Annual Report to the eLib for the Period from 1st August 1995 to 31st July 1996.
         1.2 Project Infrastructure. Available at <a href="http://www.eevl.ac.uk/document.html">http://www.eevl.ac.uk/document.html</a>.
      </p>
      
      
      
      
      <hr width="75%">
      <center>
         <h3>8.2. Staff Training</h3>
      </center>
      
      <p>The nature of the Web and the characteristics of free Web resources challenge traditional collection-development and -management
         practices. This reality requires that staff receive training and supervision. The DESIRE Handbook recommends developing the
         following:
         
         <ul>
            
            <li>exercises and examples for evaluating Web sites</li>
            
            <li>online tutorials</li>
            
            <li>staff manuals</li>
            
            <li>process to review sites selected by staff</li>
            
            <li>group e-mail lists to discuss and debate quality issues</li>
            
            <li>editorial meetings</li>
            
         </ul>
         Many quality sites are added to collections through user suggestions by means of "Contact us" or "Add new resource" buttons.
         Training users of such sites to become informed selectors is neither appropriate nor feasible; however, some means of quality
         control
         
         
         <hr width="75%">
         <p align="center"><i>-33-</i></p>
         
         should be maintained. The Humbul Humanities Hub has a policy that requires contributions from users whose credentials and
         selection criteria are unknown or cannot be judged to be reviewed, evaluated, and cataloged by staff.
      </p>
      
      <p><b>Recommended Staff Training Practices</b></p>
      
      <p><i>DESIRE Information Gateways Handbook</i>. 1.3. Staff and Skills Required Overview. Available at <a href="http://www.desire.org/handbook/1-3.html">http://www.desire.org/handbook/1-3.html</a>.
      </p>
      
      <p><i>DESIRE Information Gateways Handbook</i>. 2.1. Quality Selection: Training Staff. Available at <a href="http://www.desire.org/handbook/2-1.html">http://www.desire.org/handbook/2-1.html</a>.
      </p>
      
